         <abstract>
            <p>The most recent crisis was not basically about sterling but it did demonstrate again the importance of sterling in the international monetary system. Clearly there is an obvious need to introduce a greater degree of stability into the present system and this movement towards stability will be greatly enhanced by the elimination of our own balance of payments deficit. Even with the introduction of the Special Drawing Rights, the system will remain unstable if the reserve currencies continue to run large balance of payments deficits. It is for this reason that the U.K. Government has put the achievement of a large and lasting surplus in our balance of payments as its first economic priority. The stakes in this particular game are very high but fortunately the players are acutely aware of the costs of failure--economically and politically.</p>
          </abstract>
